msgid "Examples in API docs"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:87
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:460
msgid ""
"Everything should have examples. Here is an example of how to do examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:89
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:462
msgid ""
"````\n"
"/// # Examples\n"
"///\n"
"/// ```\n"
"/// use op;\n"
"///\n"
"/// let s = \"foo\";\n"
"/// let answer = op::compare(s, \"bar\");\n"
"/// ```\n"
"///\n"
"/// Passing a closure to compare with, rather than a string:\n"
"///\n"
"/// ```\n"
"/// use op;\n"
"///\n"
"/// let s = \"foo\";\n"
"/// let answer = op::compare(s, |a| a.chars().is_whitespace().all());\n"
"/// ```\n"
"````"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:109
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:482
msgid "Referring to types"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:112
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:485
msgid ""
"When talking about a type, use its full name. In other words, if the type is "
"generic, say `Option<T>`, not `Option`. An exception to this is bounds. "
"Write `Cow<'a, B>` rather than `Cow<'a, B> where B: 'a + ToOwned + ?Sized`."
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:116
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:489
msgid ""
"Another possibility is to write in lower case using a more generic term. In "
"other words, ‘string’ can refer to a `String` or an `&str`, and ‘an option’ "
"can be ‘an `Option<T>`’."
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:119
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:492
msgid "Link all the things"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:122
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:495
msgid ""
"A major drawback of Markdown is that it cannot automatically link types in "
"API documentation. Do this yourself with the reference-style syntax, for "
"ease of reading:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:125
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:498
msgid ""
"```\n"
"/// The [`String`] passed in lorum ipsum...\n"
"///\n"
"/// [`String`]: ../string/struct.String.html\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:131
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:504
msgid "Module-level vs type-level docs"
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:134
#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:507
msgid ""
"There has often been a tension between module-level and type-level "
"documentation. For example, in today's standard library, the various `*Cell` "
"docs say, in the pages for each type, to \"refer to the module-level "
"documentation for more details.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/1574-more-api-documentation-conventions.md:139
msgid ""
"Instead, module-level documentation should show a high-level summary of "
"everything in the module, and each type should document itself fully. It is "
"okay if there is some small amount of duplication here. Module-level "
"documentation should be broad and not go into a lot of detail. That is left "
"to the type's documentation."
msgstr ""

